import DocsLayout from "../layouts/DocsLayout.astro";
---

<DocsLayout title="Features — hemingway-ai" heading="Features">
  <h2>Text discovery</h2>
  <p>
    Hemingway uses a TreeWalker to find editable text elements on your page:
    H1–H6, P, SPAN, A, BUTTON, LI, LABEL, TD, TH. It ignores script tags,
    style tags, and hidden elements.
  </p>

  <h2>Copy job classification</h2>
  <p>Every selected element gets classified by its role:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><code>primary-headline</code> — H1 elements</li>
    <li><code>cta-label</code> — Buttons and CTA links</li>
    <li><code>section-opener</code> — First paragraph in a section</li>
    <li><code>body-copy</code> — Other paragraphs</li>
    <li><code>feature-point</code> — List items</li>
    <li><code>eyebrow</code> — Short text before headings</li>
    <li><code>testimonial</code> — Quoted testimonials</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Section role detection</h2>
  <p>
    Hemingway infers what part of the page you're editing — hero, problem
    statement, solution, features, social proof, pricing, CTA, or footer — and
    adjusts its suggestions accordingly.
  </p>

  <h2>Page context</h2>
  <p>
    When you select text, hemingway builds a full brief: the page title,
    narrative stage (opening/middle/closing), primary goal, core promise, and
    section flow. This context helps Claude generate alternatives that fit
    naturally.
  </p>

  <h2>Multi-select</h2>
  <p>
    Hold Cmd (Mac) or Ctrl (Windows) and click 2–5 elements. Hemingway generates
    cohesive alternatives across all selected elements so the copy reads as a
    unified whole.
  </p>

  <h2>Inline editing</h2>
  <p>
    Double-click any text element to edit it directly. Press Enter or click away
    to commit. The change writes back to your source files.
  </p>

  <h2>Write-back</h2>
  <p>
    When you apply an alternative, hemingway finds the original text in your
    source files using heuristic matching with encoding-aware variants (HTML
    entities, curly quotes, etc.). It scores matches by tag name, CSS classes,
    and parent context to pick the right one.
  </p>

  <h2>Style learning</h2>
  <p>
    Every time you pick an alternative, hemingway records your preference. After
    a few picks, it feeds your top style preferences back into future generations
    so suggestions get better over time.
  </p>

  <h2>Style guide &amp; copy bible</h2>
  <p>
    Point hemingway at your brand style guide and copy bible via config. These
    documents are included in every generation prompt, so Claude follows your
    brand voice, terminology, and conventions.
  </p>
</DocsLayout>
